  "prompt": "What do the meiosis phases look like?",
  "response": "Here's a summary of the meiosis phases:\n\nMeiosis I:\n1. Prophase I\n- Homologous chromosomes pair up\n- Crossing over occurs\n- Chromosomes condense\n- Nuclear membrane breaks down\n\n2. Metaphase I\n- Homologous chromosome pairs line up at cell's equator\n- Each pair attached to spindle fibers\n\n3. Anaphase I\n- Homologous chromosomes separate\n- Move to opposite cell poles\n- Chromosomes are still duplicated\n\n4. Telophase I\n- Chromosomes reach cell poles\n- Cell divides into two daughter cells\n- Chromosomes remain condensed\n\nMeiosis II:\n1. Prophase II\n- Chromosomes remain condensed\n- Spindle fibers form\n\n2. Metaphase II\n- Chromosomes align at cell's equator\n- Chromosomes are now single\n\n3. Anaphase II\n- Sister chromatids separate\n- Move to opposite cell poles\n\n4. Telophase II\n- Chromosomes reach cell poles\n- Four haploid daughter cells form\n- Nuclear membranes reform\n\nEach phase involves specific chromosome and cellular changes leading to genetic variation.",
